The Abipones render themselves formidable to the eyeS, as well as to the ears of their ene- mies ; sor they prelude every battle with trum- petS, fiutes, horns, and clarions, differing in sound, materiaIS, and form. The horn instru- ments bellow‚ the wooden ones datter, and those of bone, Which are made of the leg of some large bird or quadruped, emit a very shrill whistle, while those of reeds have a ridiculous creaking sound. Others again, consisting of the tail of the armadillo, to which a reed is pre— fixed, fill the whole air, to a great distance, with a horrible roaring. I want words to describe the construction and use of all the different trumpets. This is very certain, that the Abi- pones have more trumpeters than soldiers in their armies.
